body:
Hi,
Thanks for maintaining Verilator, it helps us a lot!

Today I got `SIGSEGV` when calling SystemVerilog task from C function through DPI-C, using Verilator v5.008(tag) that is built from source using g++ on Ubuntu 20.04.
The minimal code that reproduces the problem is as follows.

`top.sv`:
```systemverilog
`default_nettype none
`timescale 1ns/1ps

module TOP;

    localparam cycle = 1000.0 / 100.0;
    localparam halfcycle = 0.5 * cycle;

    logic clk = '0;

    import "DPI-C" context task tb_c_wait();

    export "DPI-C" task tb_sv_wait;
    task automatic tb_sv_wait(input int n);
        $display("tb_sv_wait(", n, ")");
        repeat(n) @(negedge clk); // if we comment this line out, it works.
    endtask

    initial begin
        forever begin
            #halfcycle clk = ~clk;
        end
    end

    initial begin
        $display("calling tb_c_wait...");
        repeat(10) @(posedge clk);
        tb_c_wait();
        repeat(10) @(posedge clk);
        $finish();
    end

endmodule
`default_nettype wire
```

`dpi.c`:
```c
#include "VTOP__Dpi.h"
#include <stdio.h>

int tb_c_wait()
{
    printf("calling tb_sv_wait...\n");
    fflush(stdout);
    tb_sv_wait(10);
    printf("done!\n");
    fflush(stdout);
    return 0;
}
```

And I compiled the code with the following `Makefile`:

```make
.DEFAULT_GOAL := all

VERILATOR_MAKE_FLAGS = --compiler gcc -MAKEFLAGS "CXX=g++-11 LINK=g++-11 VERILATOR_ROOT=/path/to/verilator5 -j4"
all: dpi.c top.sv Makefile
        @verilator --version
        verilator --binary -sv -Wno-BLKANDNBLK $(VERILATOR_MAKE_FLAGS) --top-module TOP top.sv dpi.c
```

It appears that the problem occurs when the internally-defined `VTOP___024root____Vdpiexp_TOP__DOT__tb_sv_wait_TOP` is called.
Since the task does `@(negedge clock)`, the function uses `co_await` and therefore returns `VlCoroutine`. But the alias type `VTOP__Vcb_tb_sv_wait_t` defined in `VTOP__Syms.h` returns `void`.

I have written a simple patch to fix this problem and am now writing a PullReq.
Could you take a look at it when you have a moment?

Thanks in advance.
